revision.text:
{{Refimprove science|date=November 2017}} [[File:Amplituhedron-0c.png|thumb]] An '''amplituhedron''' is a geometric structure introduced in 2013 by [[Nima Arkani-Hamed]] and Jaroslav Trnka. It enables simplified calculation of [[particle]] interactions in some [[quantum field]] theories. In [[Planar Yang–Mills theory|planar ''N'' = 4 supersymmetric Yang–Mills theory]], also equivalent to the perturbative [[Topological string theory#B-model|topological B model string theory]] in [[twistor space]], an amplituhedron is defined as a mathematical space known as the positive [[Grassmannian]].{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}}<ref name="Witten">{{cite journal|last=Witten|first=Edward|title=Perturbative Gauge Theory As A String Theory In Twistor Space:|journal=Communications in Mathematical Physics|date=December 2003|volume=252|series=1|issue=1|page=189|doi=10.1007/s00220-004-1187-3|arxiv=hep-th/0312171|bibcode = 2004CMaPh.252..189W }}</ref>
Amplituhedron theory challenges the notion that [[Spacetime|space-time]] [[Principle of locality|locality]] and [[unitarity (physics)|unitarity]] are necessary components of a model of particle interactions. Instead, they are treated as properties that emerge from an underlying phenomenon.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Bourjaily|Cachazo|Goncharov|2012}}<ref name=ohanlon20130919>{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/how-to-feel-about-space-and-time-maybe-not-existing-76578241dca2|title=How to Feel About Space and Time Maybe Not Existing|publisher=Pacific Standard|author= Ryan O'Hanlon | date=September 19, 2013}}</ref>
The connection between the amplituhedron and scattering amplitudes is at present a conjecture that has passed many non-trivial checks, including an understanding of how locality and unitarity arise as consequences of positivity.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}}
Research has been led by [[Nima Arkani-Hamed]]. [[Edward Witten]] described the work as “very unexpected" and said that "it is difficult to guess what will happen or what the lessons will turn out to be."<ref name="Quandra20130917">{{cite web|url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/physicists-discover-geometry-underlying-particle-physics-20130917/|title=A Jewel at the Heart of Quantum Physics|author=Natalie Wolchover|publisher=Quanta Magazine|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref>
== Description == When [[subatomic particle]]s interact, different outcomes are possible. The evolution of the various possibilities is called a "tree" and the probability of a given outcome is called its [[scattering amplitude]]. According to the principle of [[unitarity (physics)|unitarity]], the sum of the probabilities for every possible outcome is 1.
The [[On shell and off shell|on-shell]] scattering process "tree" may be described by a positive [[Grassmannian]], a structure in [[algebraic geometry]] analogous to a [[convex polytope]], that generalizes the idea of a [[simplex]] in [[projective space]].{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Bourjaily|Cachazo|Goncharov|2012}} A [[polytope]] is the ''n''-dimensional analogue of a 3-dimensional [[polyhedron]], the values being calculated in this case are scattering amplitudes, and so the object is called an ''amplituhedron''.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}}
Using [[twistor theory]], [[BCFW recursion]] relations involved in the scattering process may be represented as a small number of twistor diagrams. These diagrams effectively provide the recipe for constructing the positive Grassmannian, i.e. the amplituhedron, which may be captured in a single equation.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Bourjaily|Cachazo|Goncharov|2012}} The scattering amplitude can thus be thought of as the volume of a certain polytope, the positive Grassmannian, in momentum twistor space.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2013}}
When the volume of the amplituhedron is calculated in the [[1/N expansion|planar limit]] of [[N = 4 super Yang–Mills|''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;4 ''D''&nbsp;=&nbsp;4 supersymmetric Yang–Mills theory]], it describes the [[scattering amplitude]]s of [[subatomic particles]].{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}} The amplituhedron thus provides a more intuitive geometric model for calculations whose underlying principles were until then highly abstract.{{sfn|4 gravitons and a grad student|2013}}
The twistor-based representation provides a recipe for constructing specific cells in the Grassmannian which assemble to form a positive Grassmannian, i.e. the representation describes a specific [[cellular decomposition|cell decomposition]] of the positive Grassmannian.
The recursion relations can be resolved in many different ways, each giving rise to a different representation, with the final amplitude expressed as a sum of on-shell processes in different ways as well. Therefore, any given on-shell representation of scattering amplitudes is not unique, but all such representations of a given interaction yield the same amplituhedron.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}}
The twistor approach is relatively abstract. While amplituhedron theory provides an underlying geometric model, the geometrical space is not physical spacetime and is also best understood as abstract.<ref name="ananth2017">Ananthaswamy, 2017</ref>
==Implications==
The twistor approach simplifies calculations of particle interactions. In a conventional [[Perturbation theory (quantum mechanics)|perturbative]] approach to quantum field theory, such interactions may require the calculation of thousands of [[Feynman diagrams]], most describing off-shell "virtual" particles which have no directly observable existence. In contrast, [[twistor theory]] provides an approach in which scattering amplitudes can be computed in a way that yields much simpler expressions.<ref name=drum20130918>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2013/09/space-time-illusion-amplituhedron|title=Maybe Space-Time Is Just an Illusion|author=Kevin Drum|publisher=Mother Jones|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref> Amplituhedron theory calculates scattering amplitudes without referring to such virtual particles. This undermines the case for even a transient, unobservable existence for such virtual particles.<ref>{{Citation|last=GraduatePhysics|title=Nima Arkani-Hamed - Physics and Mathematics for the End of Spacetime|date=2016-07-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z1-QDXReDTU|accessdate=2017-05-28}}</ref><ref name="ananth2017"/>
The geometric nature of the theory suggests in turn that the nature of the universe, in both classical [[Theory of relativity|relativistic]] [[spacetime]] and [[quantum mechanics]], may be described with [[geometry]].<ref name="ananth2017"/>
Calculations can be done without assuming the quantum mechanical properties of [[Principle of locality|locality]] and [[Unitarity (physics)|unitarity]]. In amplituhedron theory, locality and unitarity arise as a direct consequence of positivity.{{clarify|reason=what is positivity in this context?|date=April 2017}} They are encoded in the positive geometry of the amplituhedron, via the singularity structure of the integrand for scattering amplitudes.{{sfn|Arkani-Hamed|Trnka|2014}} Arkani-Hamed suggests this is why amplituhedron theory simplifies scattering-amplitude calculations: In the Feynman-diagrams approach, locality is manifest, whereas in the amplituhedron approach, it is implicit.<ref>Musser, George (2015). ''Spooky Action at a Distance'', pp. 40–41. Farrar, Straus and Giroux, New York. {{ISBN|9780374536619}}.</ref>
Since the planar limit of the ''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;4 supersymmetric Yang–Mills theory is a [[toy theory]] that does not describe the real world, the relevance of this technique for more realistic quantum field theories is currently unknown, but it provides promising directions for research into theories about the real world.
