In a [[linear panel]] data setting, it can be desirable to estimate the magnitude of the [[Fixed Effects]], as they provide measures of the [[unobserved components]]. For instance, in [[wage equation]] regressions, Fixed Effects capture [[Aptitude|ability]] measures that are constant over time, such as motivation. [[Gary Chamberlain|Chamberlain]]'s approach to unobserved effects models is a way of estimating the linear unobserved effects, under Fixed Effect (rather than [[Random Effects]]) assumptions, in the following unobserved effects model

''y<sub>it</sub> = x<sub>it</sub>b + c<sub>i</sub> + u<sub>it</sub>	''																			(1)

where ''c<sub>i</sub>'' is the unobserved effect and ''x<sub>it</sub>'' contains only time-varying [[explanatory variables]].<ref>Wooldridge, J. (2002): Econometric Analysis of Cross Section and Panel Data, MIT Press, Cambridge, Mass.</ref>  Rather than [[differencing out]] the unobserved effect ''c<sub>i</sub>'', Chamberlain proposed to replace it with the [[linear projection]] of it onto the explanatory variables in all time periods. Specifically, this leads to the following equation

''c<sub>i</sub> = d + x<sub>i1</sub> λ<sub>1</sub> + x<sub>i2</sub> λ<sub>2</sub> + ... + x<sub>iT</sub> λ<sub>T</sub> + e<sub>i</sub>	''														(2)

where the conditional distribution of ''c<sub>i</sub>''  given ''x<sub>it</sub>'' is unspecified, as is standard in Fixed Effects models. Combining equations (1) and (2) then gives rise to the following model.<ref>Chamberlain, G. (1982): Multivariate Regression Models for Panel Data. Journal of Econometrics (18), pp. 5-46</ref><ref>Chamberlain, G. (1984): Panel Data. Handbook of Econometrics, Volume 2, ed. Z. Griliches and M. D. Intriligator. Amsterdam: North Holland, pp. 1247-1318</ref>

''y<sub>it</sub> = d + x<sub>i1</sub> λ<sub>1</sub> + ... + x<sub>it</sub> (b+λ<sub>t</sub> ) + ... + x<sub>iT</sub> λ<sub>Tb</sub> + e<sub>i</sub> + u<sub>it</sub>''												(3)

An important advantage of this approach is the [[computational]] requirement. Chamberlain uses [[minimum distance estimation]], but a [[Mixture model#Gaussian mixture model|GMM]] approach would be another valid way of estimating this model. The latter approach also gives rise to a larger number of instruments than moment conditions, which leads to useful [[overidentifying restrictions]] that can be used to test the [[strict exogeneity restrictions]] imposed by many [[Static variable|static]] Fixed Effects models.<ref>Wooldridge, J. (2002): Econometric Analysis of Cross Section and Panel Data, MIT Press, Cambridge, Mass.</ref>

Similar approaches have been proposed to model the unobserved effect. For instance, Mundlak follows a very similar approach, but rather projects the unobserved effect ''c<sub>i</sub>'' onto the average of all ''x<sub>it</sub>'' across all T time periods, more specifically <ref>Mundlak, Y. (1978): On the Pooling of Time Series and Cross Section Data. Econometrica (46), pp. 69-85</ref>

''c<sub>i</sub> = d + <span style="text-decoration:overline">x</span><sub>i</sub>λ + e<sub>i</sub>''																				(4)

It can be shown that the Chamberlain method is a generalization of Mundlak's model. The Chamberlain method has been popular in [[empirical work]], ranging from studies trying to estimate the [[causal]] returns to [[Trade union|union]] members <ref>Card, D. (1996): The effect of unions on the structure of wages: a longitudinal analysis. Econometrica (64), pp. 957-979</ref> to studies investigating [[growth convergence]].<ref>Islam, N. (1995): Growth Empirics: A Panel Data Approach. The Quarterly Journal of Economics (110), pp. 1127-1170</ref>

