{{merge to|Convex set|discuss=Talk:Convex set#Proposed merge with Complex convexity|date=September 2018}} {{notability|date=October 2017}} {{technical|date=October 2017}} {{lead missing|date=March 2016}} == Definition == A set <math>\Omega</math> in <math>\mathbb{C}^n</math> is called <math>\mathbb{C}</math>-convex if its intersection with any complex line is contractible.<ref>{{citation | last1 = Andersson | first1 = Mats | last2 = Passare | first2 = Mikael | last3 = Sigurdsson | first3 = Ragnar | doi = 10.1007/978-3-0348-7871-5 | isbn = 3-7643-2420-1 | mr = 2060426 | publisher = Birkhäuser Verlag, Basel | series = Progress in Mathematics | title = Complex convexity and analytic functionals | volume = 225 | year = 2004}}.</ref>
== Background == In [[complex geometry]] and [[complex analysis|analysis]], the notion of [[convex function|convexity]] and its generalizations play an important role in understanding [[function (mathematics)|function]] behavior. Examples of classes of functions with a rich structure are, in addition to the convex functions, the [[subharmonic function]]s and the [[plurisubharmonic function]]s. Geometrically, these classes of functions correspond to convex domains and pseudoconvex domains, but there are also other types of domains, for instance lineally convex domains which can be generalized using [[convex analysis]]. A great deal is already known about these domains, but there remain some fascinating, unsolved problems. This theme is mainly theoretical, but there are computational aspects of the domains studied, and these computational aspects are certainly worthy of further study.
