'''Cyrus Colton MacDuffee''' (June 29, 1895 – August 21, 1961) from [[Oneida, New York]] was a professor of mathematics at [[University of Wisconsin]]. He wrote a number of influential research papers in [[abstract algebra]]. MacDuffee served on the Council of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (A.M.S.), was editor of the ''[[Transactions of the American Mathematical Society|Transactions of the A.M.S.]]'', and served as president of the [[Mathematical Association of America]] (M.A.A).<ref name="maa">[http://www.maa.org/history/presidents/macduffee.html MAA presidents: Cyrus Colton MacDuffee]</ref><ref name="osu">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120729121107/http://www.math.osu.edu/history/biographies/CyrusMacDuffee.html Biography from Ohio State University]</ref><ref name="mactutor">{{MacTutor|id=MacDuffee}}</ref>
MacDuffee obtained his B.S. degree in 1917 from [[Colgate University]] and a Ph.D. in 1922 from the [[University of Chicago]] ; his thesis was on [[Nonassociative algebra]]s under the direction of [[Leonard E. Dickson]]. In 1935, MacDuffee joined the University of Wisconsin, where he remained until his death in 1961. He served as chair of the department(1951–56). Later, Wisconsin endowed a university chair under his name. Prior to joining the University of Wisconsin, he served at [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and [[Ohio State University|Ohio State]].<ref name="maa"/><ref name="osu"/><ref name="mactutor"/> He guided 30 Ph.D. students, among them [[D. R. Fulkerson]], [[H. J. Ryser]], and [[Bonnie Stewart]].<ref>{{mathgenealogy|id=6071}}</ref>
