{{Infobox block cipher | name = M8 | designers = [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]] | publish date = 1999 | derived from = [[M6 (cipher)|M6]] | derived to = | related to = | key size = | block size = 64 bits | structure = [[Feistel cipher|Feistel network]] | rounds = 10 | cryptanalysis = }} In [[cryptography]], '''M8''' is a [[block cipher]] designed by [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]] in 1999. It is a modification of Hitachi's earlier [[M6 (cipher)|M6]] algorithm, designed for greater security and high performance in both hardware and 32-bit software implementations.
Like M6, M8 is a 10-round [[Feistel cipher]] with a [[block size (cryptography)|block size]] of 64 bits. The round function can include [[bit rotation]]s, [[XOR]]s, and [[modular arithmetic|modular addition]], but the structure of each round function used is determined by the [[key (cryptography)|key]]. Making these variations key-dependent is intended to make [[cryptanalysis]] more difficult (see [[FROG]] for a similar design philosophy).
