{{about|the mathematician|the athlete|Morton Browne}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2015}}
'''Morton Brown''' (born August 12, 1931, in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) is an American mathematician, who specializes in [[geometric topology]].

In 1958 Brown earned his Ph.D. from the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] under [[R. H. Bing]]. From 1960 to 1962 he was at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]]. Afterwards he became a professor at the [[University of Michigan at Ann Arbor]].

With [[Barry Mazur]] in 1965 he won the [[Oswald Veblen prize]]<ref>http://www.ams.org/profession/prizes-awards/ams-prizes/veblen-prize</ref> for their independent and nearly simultaneous proofs of the [[Schönflies problem|generalized Schoenflies hypothesis]]<ref>{{cite journal |author=Brown, Morton |year=1960 |title= A proof of the generalized Schoenflies theorem |journal= Bull. Amer. Math. Soc. |volume=66 |pages=74–76 |doi=10.1090/s0002-9904-1960-10400-4}} {{MathSciNet| id = 0117695}}</ref> in geometric topology. Brown's short proof was elementary and fully general. Mazur's proof was also elementary, but it used a special assumption which was removed via later work of Morse.

In 2012 he became a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2012-11-10.</ref>

